            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How to convert imperial pints to liters</h2>
              <p>
                In the UK and some Commonwealth countries, beer, cider, and some
                milk are still sold in
                <strong>imperial pints</strong>. Most recipes and packaging,
                however, use the metric system in <strong>liters</strong>. This
                converter helps you move accurately between the two.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Exact conversion factor</p>
                <p class="mb-1">By definition:</p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  1 imperial gallon = 4.54609 L<br />
                  1 imperial gallon = 8 imperial pints
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">Therefore:</p>
                <p>
                  \(1\ \text{imperial pint} = \dfrac{4.54609}{8} = 0.56826125\
                  \text{L}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Formula: imperial pints to liters</h3>
              <p>To convert from imperial pints (UK pt) to liters (L):</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{liters} = \text{imperial pints} \times 0.56826125\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: 4 imperial pints to liters</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Start with the volume in imperial pints: 4 pt</li>
                <li>Multiply by the conversion factor 0.56826125:</li>
              </ol>
              <p>\(4 \times 0.56826125 = 2.273045\ \text{L}\)</p>
              <p>
                Rounded to 2 decimal places, 4 imperial pints ≈
                <strong>2.27 L</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>Formula: liters to imperial pints</h3>
              <p>To go the other way, from liters to imperial pints:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{imperial pints} = \dfrac{\text{liters}}{0.56826125}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: 2 liters to imperial pints</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Start with the volume in liters: 2 L</li>
                <li>Divide by 0.56826125:</li>
              </ol>
              <p>\(\dfrac{2}{0.56826125} \approx 3.520\ \text{pt}\)</p>
              <p>So 2 liters ≈ <strong>3.52 imperial pints</strong>.</p>

              <h2>Imperial vs US pints – don’t mix them up</h2>
              <p>
                A common source of error is confusing
                <strong>imperial pints</strong> with
                <strong>US liquid pints</strong>. They are not the same size:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 imperial pint = <strong>568.26125 mL</strong></li>
                <li>1 US liquid pint = <strong>473.176473 mL</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                That means an imperial pint is about
                <strong>20% larger</strong> than a US pint. If a UK recipe calls
                for “1 pint of stock”, it usually means an imperial pint (~0.57
                L), not a US pint (~0.47 L).
              </p>

              <h2>Typical uses for imperial pints to liters</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cooking and baking</strong> with older UK cookbooks
                  that use pints.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Beer and cider</strong> volumes when comparing pub
                  servings to bottled volumes in liters.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Homebrewing</strong> when recipes or equipment are
                  specified in imperial units.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Converting packaging</strong> (e.g., milk in pints vs
                  liters on nutrition labels).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Approximate mental math shortcuts</h2>
              <p>
                If you don’t need exact precision, these rules of thumb are
                handy:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  1 imperial pint ≈ <strong>0.57 L</strong> (just over half a
                  liter)
                </li>
                <li>2 imperial pints ≈ <strong>1.1 L</strong></li>
                <li>4 imperial pints ≈ <strong>2.3 L</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For anything more precise—especially recipes or lab work—use the
                exact factor and the calculator above.
              </p>
